    "summary": "The Berlin Airlift was the Western Allied response to the Soviet Union's blockade of West Berlin from June 1948 to May 1949. After the Western powers introduced a new currency in their occupation zones, the Soviet Union closed all road, rail, and canal access to West Berlin, hoping to force a Western withdrawal from the city. Rather than abandon the two million residents of West Berlin or attempt a dangerous armed convoy, the United States, Britain, and France organized a massive sustained airlift.\n\nFor over a year, Allied aircraft flew continuous sorties into West Berlin's Tempelhof Airport and other landing strips, delivering food, fuel, and supplies. At the airlift's peak, planes landed every few minutes, and over 2.3 million tons of supplies were delivered across roughly 200,000 flights. The logistical achievement was extraordinary and transformed West Berliners' perception of their former enemies into protectors. The \"candy bombers\" — pilots who dropped chocolate and candy for children — became symbols of goodwill.\n\nThe Soviet Union lifted the blockade in May 1949, having failed to dislodge the Western powers. The Berlin Airlift was an early and decisive test of Western resolve in the [[event:113|Cold War]], demonstrating that the United States would sustain a costly, open-ended commitment to resist Soviet pressure without resorting to military confrontation. Berlin remained a divided but symbolically charged city for the next four decades.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berlin_Blockade#Airlift",
